Describe the ion transport mechanisms used by different segments of the nephron 

Tubule segments all have specialised epithelia.  

 

 

 

Types of pumps 

 

 

Primary active transport occurs at the basolateral membrane to produce an electrochemical gradient, and ion antiporters then allow for exchange as secondary active transport. Note that both transcellular (through channels) and paracellular (between epithelial cells depending on tightness of junctions between cells) pathways of tubule transport exist. 

 

 

Early proximal tubule 

 

Active reabsorption of Na+, Cl-, PO43-, amino acids; H2O and glucose follow 

Thin descending loop 

Passive H2O reabsorption 

Thick ascending loop 

Active reabsorption of Na+, K+, Cl-, paracellular reabsorption of Mg2+, Ca2+ 

Distal convoluted tubule 

Active reabsorption of Na+, Cl-, paracellular reabsorption of Ca2+ 

Collecting tubule 

Secretion of H+ and K+ by aldosterone, causing Na+ reabsorption; H2O reabsorption furthered by ADH 

 

Describe the renal handling of Na+, K+, and how this is linked to volume homeostasis 

 

Regulation of Na+ and Cl- transport 

Glomerulotubular balance is defined as the ability for the tubules to increase reabsorption rate in response to increased tubular load. There are four pathways that regulate effective circulating volume by modulating Na+ reabsorption: 

1, RAAS: Angiotensin II binds to AT1 receptors at both the apical and basolateral membranes of proximal tubule cells to promote Na+ reabsorption. Activation of the AT1 receptor at the basolateral membrane acts on the nucleus to reduce expression of the Na+/glucose influx symporter. Aldosterone reception causes the nucleus to increase expression of Na+ influx channels in the distal convoluted tubule, cortical collecting tubule and medullary collecting ducts.  

2, Sympathetic nerve stimulation: decreases renal blood flow to reduce Na+ excretion, and alpha adrenoreceptors on proximal tubules cause Na+ reabsorption. 

3, Arginine vasopressin/ADH: undergoes cAMP signaling to increase apical surface aquaporins in the cell membrane in the distal convoluted tubule and collecting duct, produces urine with high osmolality 

4, Atrial natriuretic peptide promotes natriuresis  (sodium excretion) 

 

K+ regulation 

The distal tubule reabsorbs small amounts of K+ which can be lifesaving in dietary K+ deficiency. Otherwise in normal to high dietary K+, the distal K+ secretory system is responsible for most of the K+ urinary excretion.  

 

Briefly describe the sources of creatinine and urea and their handling in the kidney 

NH4+ is the primary nitrogenous end product of amino acid catabolism. Urea is generated from NH4+ as it is much less toxic.  

 

Creatine is used for energy production in muscles, and around 2% of the body's creatine is broken down into creatinine every day.  

 

Describe how the renal handling of creatinine and urea differs in situations of volume depletion 

 

Urea transport 

Both paracellular and transcellular paths are taken by urea. Note that some urea is passed in stool and sweat. The kidney filters urea into the filtrate, secretes it into the filtrate, and reabsorbs it into the blood. More urea is reabsorbed than secreted. Compared to the filtered load, 50% is reabsorbed in the PCT, then 60% secreted in the loop of Henle, then 70% reabsorbed in the medullary collecting duct. Hence, 40% of the filtered load is actually passed in urine. Urea excretion vs urine flow (or GFR) is not a linear relationship. There is an exponential drop in urea excretion as GFR decreases.  

 

Note that H2O reabsorption in the PCT drives urea reabsorption via concentration gradient. Passive facilitated diffusion through urea transporters occurs in the distal tubule.  

 

Creatinine 

Serum creatinine is produced by the body's muscle at a constant rate, and is almost completely filtered at the glomerulus with some secretion in the PCT. Creatinine is not reabsorbed, and is nearly all excreted by the kidneys. Hence, changes in serum creatinine closely reflect changes in GFR. Other compounds that are completely filtered by the glomerulus and can be used to estimate GFR are inulin and radio-labelled EDTA (ethyl-diamine tetra-acetic acid).  

 

Acid balance 

The kidneys reabsorb nearly all filtered HCO3- and secrete into the urine the daily production of nonvolatile acids. The components of net urinary acid excretion are: 1, H+ bound to phosphate and phosphoric acid, creatinine, uric acid; 2, H+ bound as NH4+; 3, small amounts of HCO3-.
